						          			<div class="more">
										<p>Initially, I acquired a Google Home because I was curious and thought that it would be cool to have one. I read somewhere that, unfortunately, many people end up using the Google Home as a “glorified kitchen radio.” To a certain extent, it can be used in that simple manner--it can be used as a timer, as an alarm clock, and can be verbally instructed to do simple things like provide estimated times of arrival to destinations and play music. For some people, that kind of functionality may work just fine.</p>
										<p>Where Google Home really shines is in its integration to a home network and partnering devices. Certain devices, like Google’s Chromecast can be almost completely verbally controlled through Google Home, down to being able to tell it what show or movie to play! Another fun thing that can be done with Chromecast integration, is that you can turn on the TV to which the Chromecast is connected by telling Google Home to turn on the Chromecast; it doesn’t work to turn off the Chromecast though. To read more about what the Google Chromecast can do, check our our [article on it-link].</p>
										<p>Fortunately, Google Home can also talk with another control device of mine called Harmony Hub, which can control any device that uses an infrared remotes, like a TV. So with one voice command telling Google Home to talk with Harmony Hub and turn on the TV, I can turn on the TV. With another voice command, I can tell Netflix to start broadcasting a show onto my TV. Two simple voice commands easily replaced the need to find any remote or press any button to watch a show on my TV. All I had to do was make up my mind!</p>
										<p>Setting up Google Home to a wi-fi network can be pretty simply done through the Google Home app. From there, integrating different devices is as simple as the partnering device makes it. The Google Home Mini is also an option for those who desire something even more simple and lower cost. The speaker is smaller, but the capabilities are the same. There is also a Google Home Max for those who want the most sound out of the device itself. However, since Google Home can work with devices that may have their own louder sound output, a Max may not be necessary. Needless to say, there is a lot to explore within the Google Home framework, and it’s definitely worth exploring.</p>   
