					          			<div class="hidden-lg hidden-md hidden-sm col-xs-8 col-xs-offset-2 bottom-space"><img src="images/chromecast.png" alt="Keypad Entry" class="img-responsive"></div>
					          			<div class="col-xs-12">
						          			<div class="more">
										<p>I adore Google’s chromecast device, and so should anyone who has a wi-fi network and a tv with an HDMI connection. Chromecast is a device that attaches to an HDMI port and uses a home wi-fi network to replicate streaming video and audio services from other devices like a smartphone, tablet, or computer. For smartphones and tablets, there is chromecast integration on many popular streaming apps like, Netflix, Hulu, HBO Now, Spotify, and Youtube. For computers, there is specialized integration on some sites, like many of the aforementioned services, while using the Google Chrome browser (using that same browser, one may replicate just about any webpage, similar to a projector--it will more successful with a more powerful computer).</p>
										<p>For apps and websites that integrate with chromecast, there will be an icon in the top right on the app or video screen that will allow broadcasting onto a TV; broadcasting is as simple as pressing the icon, choosing the Chromecast, and pressing play! The only caveat is that both the chromecast and device hosting the app or website must be connected to the same wifi network. Setup through a mobile device is pretty simple, and can be done through the google home app or through a computer. Once the chromecast is setup and connected to a wifi network, it will be visible to any capable device connected to that wi-fi network. For instance, if a friend has a chromecast setup on their wi-fi network, and you go to your friend’s house and connect to their wifi network on your smartphone, you can broadcast a Youtube video to your friend’s TV without any additional work!</p>
										<p>On some apps and websites, Chromecast integration is more complete than others. Using a smart phone with chromecast turns the phone into a simple remote for the broadcasted service, allowing you to play, pause, stop, and control volume. Using a partner device like Google Home can increase the level of functionality to include things like voice control of those same functions. With certain apps, like Netflix or HBO Now, you can even tell it what show to play! Likely, as Google Home grows in popularity, this kind of control will only increase across more apps. Because of the convenience that Chromecast offers, its ease of use, it’s expandability (you can have multiple chromecasts on the same network), and its low cost (usually about $35 for a Chromecast), I would recommend it to anyone as a gateway into home automation.</p>   
